body:
some possible solutions:
1. set the memory map to be writable everywhere.  mmap_mode='w+'. Dangerous and requires changes to a large number of files 
2. Dont use numba for finding the median until this is (hopefully) fixed. Some performance hit for what is not perhaps a common  use case: parallel run on large data (although I am doing this myself atm!).
3. Always set arrays to be writeable in the median function, as @patrickzib suggests x.setflags(write=True). Seems a bit dangerous and would not really meet the user expectations? 
4. Clone data in median if passed a non writable array (@MatthewMiddlehurst). e.g.
```
def median(X):
    if X.flags.writeable:
        return _median(X)
    else:
        X = X.copy()
        X.setflags(write=True)
        return _median(X)


@njit(fastmath=True, cache=True)
def _median(X):
    """Numba median function for a single time series."""
    return np.median(X)
``` 
Introduces a time and memory overhead, but safer than (3) 

I dont like (1) as a widespread solution. Perhaps we should profile (2), (3) and (4) and try quantify the hit, (4) seems safest

Would this work (avoids cloning)?

```python
def median(X):
    if X.flags.writeable:
        return _median(X)
    else:
        X.setflags(write=True)
        median = _median(X)
        X.setflags(write=False)
        return median
```
